3. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper introduces a novel privacy definition and provides a closed-form expression of the relationship between privacy and estimation accuracy. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.IT sub-category.
4. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper proposes an optimal privacy-preserving average consensus algorithm, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG sub-category.
5. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper discusses the privacy-preserving average consensus problem in a distributed system, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.SY sub-category.
